<paragraph id="8BEA3691E165FFCAFEE3FE9A9EEDFE39" blockId="14.[264,1323,283,910]" box="[312,416,364,390]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Remarks</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA3691E165FFCAFEE3FE629B71FC31" blockId="14.[264,1323,283,910]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
This species was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B60E165FFCAFCF8FE629B27FE11" author="Lamothe-Argumedo" box="[803,1130,404,430]" pageId="14" pageNumber="20" refString="Lamothe-Argumedo, R. (1968) Monogeneos de peces. VI. Caballerocotyla marielenae sp. nov. (Monogenea: Capsalinae), parasito de las branquias de Istiophorus greyi Jordan and Hill, de Puerto Angel, Oaxaca, Mexico. Rivista di Parassitologia, 29, 171 - 184." type="journal article" year="1968">
Lamothe­Argumedo (
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFBFFFE629B2CFE11" box="[1060,1121,404,430]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1968.0">1968</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
as a member of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFED3FE4A9E88FE6A" box="[264,453,444,469]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Caballerocotyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFED3FE4A9E88FE6A" box="[264,453,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Caballerocotyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but was later transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFCFBFE4A9CFCFE6A" box="[800,945,444,469]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFCFBFE4A9CFCFE6A" box="[800,945,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Capsaloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B60E165FFCAFC38FE4A9A67FE69" author="Lamothe-Argumedo" box="[995,1322,444,470]" pageId="14" pageNumber="20" refString="Lamothe-Argumedo, R. (1996) Monogeneos de peces. X. Especie nueva del genero Capsaloides, parasito de Tetrapturus audax de Mazatlan, Sinaloa, Mexico. Anales del Instituto de Biologia, Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico, Serie Zoologia, 67, 163 - 171." type="journal article" year="1996">
Lamothe­Argumedo (
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFB3EFE4A9A6FFE69" box="[1253,1314,444,470]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
because of the morphology of the haptoral accessory sclerites and the bifid posterior pair of septa. The number of cusps associated with the dorsomarginal body sclerites decrease posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="136E2A14E165FFCAFE43FDC29E93FDF1" box="[408,478,564,590]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1688,1712]" captionTargetBox="[332,1255,1073,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[331,1256,1066,1678]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Variation in the morphology of the dorsomarginal body sclerites of Capsaloides perugiai and those species (C. istiophori, C. marielenae and C. tetrapteri) newly synonymised with C. perugiai (present study). Note that the number of cusps associated with the crown­shaped sclerite decrease towards the posterior body region. A. C. istiophori, drawn from USNPC 63598. B. C. marielenae, drawn from CNHE 0 0 0 133. C. C. perugiai, redrawn from Setti (1898). D. C. tetrapteri, drawn from USNPC 63600. Scale bar: 10 m." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172311/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFE14FDC29E93FDF1" box="[463,478,564,590]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B). There are 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFD5FFDC29DFDFDF1" box="[644,688,564,590]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
sclerties (with 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFCBCFDC29CDEFDF1" box="[871,915,564,590]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
cusps) in the left isolated anterior group of dorsomarginal sclerites. The right isolated group of dorsomarginal sclerites has 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFAC2FDAA9A65FDC9" box="[1305,1320,604,630]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="3.0">3</number>
bi­ or tricuspid sclerites. Close examination of type­material revealed that the body shape, the morphology of the haptoral accessory sclerites (
<figureCitation id="136E2A14E165FFCAFCB4FD5A9CFBFD79" box="[879,950,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[264,367,1253,1277]" captionTargetBox="[387,1200,808,1229]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[384,1202,806,1229]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Haptoral accessory sclerites of Capsaloides perugiai and those species newly synonymised with C. perugiai. A. C. istiophori, redrawn from Yamaguti (1968). B. C. istiophori, drawn from USNPC 63598. C. C. marielenae, drawn from CNHE 0 0 0 133. D. C. perugiai, redrawn from Setti (1898). D. C. tetrapteri, drawn from USNPC 63600. Note that the only specimen of C. istiophori deposited is large and the morphology of the accessory sclerites are slightly different (B) to that drawn by Yamaguti (1968) (see A) who based his description on 28 specimens. Scale bar: 50 m." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172312/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFC7CFD5A9CFBFD79" box="[935,950,684,710]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C) and the dorsomarginal body sclerites (
<figureCitation id="136E2A14E165FFCAFEACFD229EF0FD51" box="[375,445,724,750]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1688,1712]" captionTargetBox="[332,1255,1073,1674]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[331,1256,1066,1678]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Variation in the morphology of the dorsomarginal body sclerites of Capsaloides perugiai and those species (C. istiophori, C. marielenae and C. tetrapteri) newly synonymised with C. perugiai (present study). Note that the number of cusps associated with the crown­shaped sclerite decrease towards the posterior body region. A. C. istiophori, drawn from USNPC 63598. B. C. marielenae, drawn from CNHE 0 0 0 133. C. C. perugiai, redrawn from Setti (1898). D. C. tetrapteri, drawn from USNPC 63600. Scale bar: 10 m." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172311/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFE75FD229EF0FD51" box="[430,445,724,750]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B), which end in the posterior third of the body, are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFED3FD0A9EEFFCAA" box="[264,418,764,789]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="istiophori">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFED3FD0A9EEFFCAA" box="[264,418,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. istiophori</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(described from the same host species off Hawaii), 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFBE5FD0A9B87FCAA" box="[1086,1226,764,789]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="perugiai">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFBE5FD0A9B87FCAA" box="[1086,1226,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. perugiai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFACBFD0A9E33FC82" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFACBFD0A9E37FC82" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="tetrapteri">C. tetrapteri</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
We therefore consider 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFD70FCD29C14FC82" box="[683,857,804,829]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Caballerocotyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="marielenae">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFD70FCD29C14FC82" box="[683,857,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. marielenae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFBF8FCD29BE2FC82" box="[1059,1199,804,829]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="perugiai">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFBF8FCD29BE2FC82" box="[1059,1199,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. perugiai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see also Remarks under 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFE1CFCBA9D13FCDA" box="[455,606,844,869]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="istiophori">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFE1CFCBA9D13FCDA" box="[455,606,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. istiophori</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFDB4FCBA9DBAFCDA" box="[623,759,844,869]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="perugiai">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFDB4FCBA9DBAFCDA" box="[623,759,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. perugiai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D12E165FFCAFCEEFCBA9C84FCDA" box="[821,969,844,869]" class="Monogenea" family="Capsalidae" genus="Capsaloides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Capsalidea" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="tetrapteri">
<emphasis id="B921EA83E165FFCAFCEEFCBA9C84FCDA" box="[821,969,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">C. tetrapteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B60E165FFCAFC3FFCBA9A66FCD9" author="Lamothe-Argumedo" box="[996,1323,844,870]" pageId="14" pageNumber="20" refString="Lamothe-Argumedo, R. (1968) Monogeneos de peces. VI. Caballerocotyla marielenae sp. nov. (Monogenea: Capsalinae), parasito de las branquias de Istiophorus greyi Jordan and Hill, de Puerto Angel, Oaxaca, Mexico. Rivista di Parassitologia, 29, 171 - 184." type="journal article" year="1968">
Lamothe­Argumedo (
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFB3EFCBA9A6FFCD9" box="[1253,1314,844,870]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1968.0">1968</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described the egg as rhomboidal with an appendage present on 
<number id="3D9D24B6E165FFCAFC37FC829CB6FC31" box="[1004,1019,884,910]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1.0">1</number>
pole.
</paragraph>
